    <problem>
        <question id="1">
            <text>Express $$2 + \sqrt{2} + \frac{1}{2+\sqrt{2}}+ \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}-2}$$
                in simplest form.</text>
        </question>
        <solution>
            <text>
                $$2+\sqrt{2} + \frac{1}{2 + \sqrt{2}} \cdot \frac{2-\sqrt{2}}{2-\sqrt{2}} +
                \frac{1}{-2+\sqrt{2}} \cdot \frac{-2-\sqrt{2}}{-2-\sqrt{2}}$$
                $$\frac{4}{2} + \frac{2\sqrt{2}}{2} + \frac{2-\sqrt{2}}{2} + \frac{-2-\sqrt{2}}{2}$$
                $$\frac{4 + 2\sqrt{2} + 2 - \sqrt{2} - 2 - \sqrt{2}}{2}$$
                $$\dfrac{4}{2} = 2$$
            </text>
        </solution>
    </problem>
    <problem>
        <question id="2">
            <text>At a dance party, a group of boys and girls exchange dances as follows. one boy
                dances with 5 girls, a second boy dances with 6 girls, and so on, the last boy
                dancing with all the girls. If $b$ represents the number of boys and $g$ the number
                of girls, then find $b$ in terms of $g$.</text>
        </question>
        <solution>
            <text>boy $b$ dances with $b+4$ girls, so $b = g-4$</text>
        </solution>
    </problem>
    <problem>
        <question id="3">
            <text>Find the units digit of $7^{42}+42^7$.</text>
        </question>
        <solution>
            <text>$7^{42} = 7^{40} \cdot 7^2 = (7^4)^{10}$

                $7^1=7$

                $7^2=49$

                $7^3=343$

                $7^4=2401$

                cycle repeats. 42 mod 4 is 2, so $7^{42}$ contributes 9.

                Next, $42^7 = 40^7 \cdot 2^7$. The powers of 40 do not contribute to the units
                digit, and $2^7=128$ so $42^7$ contributes 8.

                $9+8 = 17$, giving the answer 7.</text>
        </solution>
    </problem>
    <problem>
        <question id="4">
            <text>Find all $y$ such that $$1+\frac{y+3}{y-2} = \frac{3y-3}{6-y}$$</text>
        </question>
        <solution>
            <text>
                $1+\frac{y+3}{y-2} = \frac{3y-3}{6-y}$

                $\frac{y-2}{y-2}+\frac{y+3}{y-2} = \frac{3y-3}{6-y}$

                $\frac{2y+1}{y-2} = \frac{3y-3}{6-y} = 3\frac{y-3}{6-y}$

                $(6-y)(2y+1) = 3(y-2)(y-1)$

                $-2y^2+11y+6 = 3y^2-9y+6$

                $-5y^2+20y = 0$

                $-5y(y-4) = 0$

                roots are 4, 0.</text>
        </solution>
    </problem>
